(This is my first time reporting an issue, so sorry if I get something wrong. This is just something I didn't expect to see.)

The following program compiles and runs without errors or warnings:
``` rs
fn main() {
    problem(34);
}

trait Apple {
    fn twin(&self);
    fn complain(&self);
}

trait Orange {
    fn twin(&self);
    fn report(&self);
}

impl Apple for i32 {
    fn twin(&self) {
        print!("{}", self);
    }
    fn complain(&self) {
        println!("This really shouldn't work");
    }
}

impl Orange for i32 {
    fn twin(&self) {
        print!("Not {}", self);
    }
    fn report(&self) {
        println!("This doesn't seem right");
    }
}

fn problem<T: Apple + Orange>(clash: T) {
    clash.complain();
    clash.report();
}
```

The trait bound in `problem()` leads to a collision of the two `twin()`s, but this isn't detected unless I actually try to call one of them, even when methods from both traits are used. I don't know if this behaviour is intentional or not, but I couldn't find any reference to it anywhere, and it surprised me considering how strict `rustc` usually is.

